Art is often self contained. You look at a drawing, and almost instantly can take it in and say "that's pretty, I want more".

Writing often isn't. You spend a handful seconds reading a paragraph, say the intro or a major turning point, and you may be able to say "this sounds promising, there may be more - I'll dive in". Except most paragraphs are neither intros nor turning points, depite being where most of the effort is spent. And until a reader is hooked and makes it though the whole thing, they won't be able to say "that was a good story, I want more".

Same issue can be found on comics - The art takes a hit to be able to produce pages fast enough, and the story drives the whole thing, so again it's about providing good intros and turning points. Thankfully, the art lifts some weight off the reader's effort, speeding reader progress along to the nearest hook, and can even provide some hooks of it's own by inserting some double page scenic pieces where applicable.

Not the anons you're talking to, but while there's some level of subjectivity in all art, you're a retard if you're dismissing absolutely everything he's saying outright.
There's literally nothing subjective about the fact that a picture takes less time, and thus engagement, to become invested and take most of all it has to offer in. Which has a knock on effect on a myriad of aspects of the relationship between the end viewer/reader of the work and the work itself, and the creator of that work. The point isn't one is better than the other, the point is because they're fundamentally different mediums of art, it means they have different strengths and weaknesses, meaning that one is likely going to be better for some things (quicker digestion, how much content the work can have to elicit an emotional response, ease of creation for certain subject matters, etc.) than others (Have to be able to read at a competent level depending on the writing, need to be able to understand perspective and volume, etc.).
It's a pain in the ass to effectively show inner thought in an image, but it's a pain in the ass to show an exciting action scene in just writing.
